title: Socio-economic and Health Disparities in Los Angeles County, California
author: Author A. B.
summary: This study explores the impact of socio-economic indicators in Los Angeles County, California on key public health outcomes, including life expectancy, preventable hospitalizations, and chronic disease rates. Special attention is given to racial disparities and urban density as contributing factors.

statistical_analysis.findings: The study found a strong association (p < 0.01) between economic hardship and elevated ER admissions in Los Angeles County, California. Communities with low education levels and limited insurance access showed a 22–31% higher rate of hospital utilization.

policy_implication: Recommendations for Los Angeles County, California include expanding mobile health services, implementing education-linked health incentive programs, and increasing funding for local clinics in socioeconomically disadvantaged areas.
references: Los Angeles County, California Department of Health Annual Report

statistical_analysis.findings: The study found a strong association (p < 0.01) between economic hardship and elevated ER admissions in Duval County, Florida. Communities with low education levels and limited insurance access showed a 22–31% higher rate of hospital utilization.

policy_implication: Recommendations for Duval County, Florida include expanding mobile health services, implementing education-linked health incentive programs, and increasing funding for local clinics in socioeconomically disadvantaged areas.
references: Duval County, Florida Department of Health Annual Report
